+# Exploration 001 Summary
+
+- Goal:
+  choose exactly one inherited architecture and one named bad term for
+  `step-005` of the fixed-protocol exact-rewrite audit.
+- What I tried:
+  compared `De Giorgi truncation`, `local-energy flux/localization`, and
+  `vorticity stretching localization` against the recorded mission negatives in
+  `MISSION.md`, `CHAIN.md`, run-003 planning files, `step-001/RESULTS.md`,
+  `step-004/RESULTS.md`, and the CKN/Vasseur architecture notes.
+- Outcome:
+  `succeeded`.
+- One key takeaway:
+  the only source-supported architecture that does not quietly rerun an already
+  killed branch is `local-energy flux/localization`, and its audit target
+  should be the whole cutoff-flux bundle
+  `I_flux[φ;u,p] = ∬ (|u|^2 + 2p) u · ∇φ`.
+- Leads worth pursuing:
+  later steps should freeze one parabolic cutoff protocol and test only exact
+  rewrites that still act on the same bundle after all localization,
+  projection, and commutator bookkeeping.
+- Unexpected findings:
+  the strongest reason not to isolate the pressure subterm is not just prior
+  pressure failure; it is that exact rewrites naturally move cost between the
+  convective and pressure-looking pieces, so the full bundle is the only stable
+  audit target.
+- Computations worth doing later if outside scope:
+  an explicit loss ledger for the frozen cutoff protocol showing how each
+  candidate rewrite acts on `I_flux[φ;u,p]` and whether any claimed gain is
+  real, cosmetic, hybrid, or architecture-changing.
